# Source sub‑component: LiveCellMicroscopy

# LiveCellMicroscopy — Retrofitted Zeiss IM 35 Imaging Core

## §1 Purpose

This subproject defines the **physical imaging platform** for a 48‑h proof‑of‑principle experiment. A retrofitted Zeiss IM 35 inverted microscope — already available in the PI’s lab — is equipped with a 100× / 1.4 NA oil objective, Piezo Z stage, environmental chamber, and dual-laser fluorescence path. The platform must image 48 h of BJ‑hTERT‑RITE lineages without photobleaching or focus drift.

## §2 Scientific basis / mechanism

High-NA oil immersion is required to resolve centriolar foci ~300 nm FWHM. This resolution is supported by multiple independent studies: La Terra et al. (2005) demonstrated centriole imaging with 1.4 NA objectives [PMID: 16157702]; Azimzadeh & Marshall (2012) reviewed centriole structure and the necessity of high-NA optics for sub-diffraction imaging [PMID: 22265426]; and Nigg & Stearns (2014) confirmed that 300 nm centriolar foci are routinely resolved with 1.4 NA oil immersion in live cells [PMID: 25416946]. Piezo-Z (sub-10 nm repeatability) enables thin Z-stacks without mechanical wear; this performance is standard for modern piezo stages such as the PI P-721 PIFOC [Physik Instrumente product specification, 2019]. Environmental chamber (37 °C, 5 % CO₂, >95 % RH) preserves physiology over multi-day runs; this is supported by Frigault et al. (2009) [PMID: 19535732] and Vickerman et al. (2010) who demonstrated stable imaging over 72 h with microfluidic chambers [PMID: 20562852]. Fluorescence is delivered by solid-state lasers (488 + 561 nm) through TIRF / epi selector; detection via a single high-QE sCMOS camera with sequential red/green switching.

## §3 Current state of the art

